    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The danger of moist and wet avalanches will increase quickly during the day.</highlights>
      <comment>The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust and will soften quickly. In steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface. &lt;br/> As a consequence of warming, the activity of moist and wet avalanches will increase. This applies especially on very steep sunny slopes at intermediate and high altitudes, and in steep rocky terrain. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Also below approximately 2700 m and on very steep shady slopes individual medium-sized natural wet avalanches are possible as a consequence of warming during the day and solar radiation.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>The spring-like weather conditions gave rise to rapid settling of the snowpack. &lt;br/> This situation gave rise to increasing moistening of the snowpack below approximately 2700 m. &lt;br/> The amount of snow is subject to significant local variations. &lt;br/> Especially on sunny slopes below the tree line no snow is lying. On shady slopes below the tree line hardly any snow is lying. &lt;br/> Especially on the colder slopes above the treeline, in the valley basins and headlands that have been less affected by stormy winds in recent weeks, there is excellent snow cover. &lt;br/> Weak layers exist in the bottom section of the snowpack in particular at high altitudes and in high Alpine regions.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
      <highlights>As a consequence of warming during the day small and, in isolated cases, medium-sized moist and wet avalanches are possible below approximately 3300 m.</highlights>
      <tendencyType>steady</tendencyType>
